text: We've got paper and I'm checking voices and stuff. Okay, David has started the tape. He needs to check your voice. Could you tell me what the weather's like out there? Oh, the weather is more like Seattle than California. It's sort of gray and raw. Yeah, I'm from near there myself. I grew up in the Sacramento Valley and went to school at USF. Uh-huh. Yeah, I have a cousin who lives in Mill Valley. That's not too far from there, is it? No, we're over in the East Bay actually in a suburb. Yeah. Do you get into the city very often? Pardon me? Do you get into the city very often, San Francisco? Oh, yeah, we get over there fairly often. I mean, that's the main reason for living in the area. Okay. We okay, David? Tape is rolling. Okay, tape is rolling. Regarding your origins as a science fiction writer, I guess in the late 1940s. Can you recall the circumstances that started you off as a writer? Did you, for instance, start as a fan? Or how did you pick up the science fiction? Oh, well, it happened I had been reading science fiction for quite a few years. I wasn't a fan because I, in the usual sense of the word, because I didn't know any other people to speak of who read this stuff. But I used to write stories as a hobby and just for my own amusement, really. But eventually, in Fallen College, I got to talking with a friend I had then who also read science fiction, as it turned out. And in the course of conversation, an idea developed that I thought would make a good story. So I went ahead and wrote it. Then he read it and urged me to send it in. So I borrowed a typewriter, not only one at the time myself, and prepared a manuscript and sent it in. And quite some time went by, I'd almost forgotten about it all, when much to my surprise I got an acceptance. And after that I sold a few other things. I was still studying to become a physicist and graduated, but graduated into a recession when jobs were hard to find. So I thought I'd try supporting myself for a while as a freelance writer, while looking around for a more steady employment. But somehow that file got longer and longer and longer. Okay. In other words, you decided to go to be a full-time writer right after you graduated from college, is really when the decision was made. No, I didn't make that decision immediately. I sort of drifted into it in the course of the next year or so. The same way as most people really drift into whatever careers they end up in. Okay, I had a couple questions about your future history. Yours, I believe, is a lot tighter than some of the others that I've read. Did you start off your future history with a deliberate plan to, you know, with charts, with timelines, with the whole thing, or did it just grow? Well, this is a rather interesting, to me, and certainly complicated matter. How much of a story do you want on it? Oh, I don't know, just about the origins, maybe the genesis of how you started, at the point at which you got the idea you had a future history in hand. Yeah, okay, well, there have actually been two, plus a couple of others that you might perhaps call many future histories. That is to say, three or four stories on the same timeline, no more. But I started out originally rather early in my career, and more or less inspired by Heinlein's future history. I was a writer, and constructed one of my own, with charts and background material and so on, like his. Of course, mine was, in mine the events were different. But basically, I wanted to do a similar job that is fictionally tell about the story of mankind from almost the present day up at least until the early era of expansion among the stars. This wasn't going to be the only thing I did by any means. Just like Asimov, I would write other things that were not in the series. But from time to time, I'd add something to it. And I did over the years. But gradually, for a number of reasons, got less and less interested in continuing and started phasing it out, doing less and less of it. One reason for being less interested was that, as far as the early part of it, reality was catching up with me. Not only were public or political events not working out on my timetable. For example, World War III did not come off on schedule. But also, it turned out I had failed to foresee a number of scientific and technological developments. So, I was going into other things. But you're probably thinking, though, about this much larger and more enduring project of mine, which has sometimes been called the League and Empire series or something like that. Now, that has a history much more like that of Topsy. It just grew. Originally, I'd written a few stories about Nicholas Van Rijn. And I'd written a few stories about Dominic Flandry, who lived in completely different milieus, of course. And then one day, on an impulse, I thought, well, gosh, they could be on the same timeline, one living about 500 years after the other. And threw in mention of that in one of the Flandry stories. And then started fitting in other stories, wherever it was convenient. You see, the thing with the future history is that, although each story should, of course, be readable independently of any others, and comprehensible and so on, nevertheless, if you have a reader who remembers a number of them, the cross-connections will add an extra dimension, and thereby, I hope, add to his enjoyment. So, I started doing it that way. And after a while, I realized I had a rather large beast by the tail. If I was going to stay consistent at all, then I had to keep careful notes, and I had to develop a systematic scheme and so on. And thus, over the years, one thing led to another, until it all became rather elaborate. By now, it includes, oh, I think something like 40 separate items, of which probably at least a third or so are full-dress novels. But I've probably carried it about as far as it can go. I doubt I'll do much more, if anything, in that line. Instead, I'd rather go on to something else. Yeah, I've heard it called, the first portion of that, the larger future history, called the Polysotechnic League, about von Rhein and David Falkain. Did you model that on European trading leagues during the Renaissance, the history behind that, the model? Oh, I was drawing some historical parallels, of course. In the case of that phase of it, you could, you can see some obvious parallels to things like, say, the medieval Hanseatic League, and of course also to the Age of Discovery a little later. On the other hand, when you get into the imperial part of it, say, the Dominic Flandry stories, the parallels there, or to other things, like, for example, the Byzantines versus the Persians, a conflict which went on for centuries and wore up both parties. I don't, I've never tried to force these things too much. History never repeats itself exactly. History never repeats itself exactly. History never repeats itself exactly. segments.text: We've got paper and I'm checking voices and stuff.
Okay, David has started the tape.
He needs to check your voice.
Could you tell me what the weather's like out there?
Oh, the weather is more like Seattle than California.
It's sort of gray and raw.
Yeah, I'm from near there myself.
I grew up in the Sacramento Valley and went to school at USF.
Yeah, I have a cousin who lives in Mill Valley.
That's not too far from there, is it?
No, we're over in the East Bay actually in a suburb.
Do you get into the city very often?
Do you get into the city very often, San Francisco?
Oh, yeah, we get over there fairly often.
I mean, that's the main reason for living in the area.
Regarding your origins as a science fiction writer,
Can you recall the circumstances that started you off as a writer?
Did you, for instance, start as a fan?
Or how did you pick up the science fiction?
Oh, well, it happened I had been reading science fiction for quite a few years.
I wasn't a fan because I, in the usual sense of the word, because I didn't know any other people to speak of who read this stuff.
But I used to write stories as a hobby and just for my own amusement, really.
But eventually, in Fallen College, I got to talking with a friend I had then who also read science fiction, as it turned out.
And in the course of conversation, an idea developed that I thought would make a good story.
So I went ahead and wrote it.
Then he read it and urged me to send it in.
So I borrowed a typewriter, not only one at the time myself, and prepared a manuscript and sent it in.
And quite some time went by, I'd almost forgotten about it all, when much to my surprise I got an acceptance.
And after that I sold a few other things.
I was still studying to become a physicist and graduated, but graduated into a recession when jobs were hard to find.
So I thought I'd try supporting myself for a while as a freelance writer, while looking around for a more steady employment.
But somehow that file got longer and longer and longer.
In other words, you decided to go to be a full-time writer right after you graduated from college, is really when the decision was made.
No, I didn't make that decision immediately.
I sort of drifted into it in the course of the next year or so.
The same way as most people really drift into whatever careers they end up in.
Okay, I had a couple questions about your future history.
Yours, I believe, is a lot tighter than some of the others that I've read.
Did you start off your future history with a deliberate plan to, you know, with charts, with timelines, with the whole thing, or did it just grow?
Well, this is a rather interesting, to me, and certainly complicated matter.
How much of a story do you want on it?
Oh, I don't know, just about the origins, maybe the genesis of how you started, at the point at which you got the idea you had a future history in hand.
Yeah, okay, well, there have actually been two, plus a couple of others that you might perhaps call many future histories.
That is to say, three or four stories on the same timeline, no more.
But I started out originally rather early in my career, and more or less inspired by Heinlein's future history.
I was a writer, and constructed one of my own, with charts and background material and so on, like his.
Of course, mine was, in mine the events were different.
But basically, I wanted to do a similar job that is fictionally tell about the story of mankind from almost the present day up at least until the early era of expansion among the stars.
This wasn't going to be the only thing I did by any means.
Just like Asimov, I would write other things that were not in the series.
But from time to time, I'd add something to it.
And I did over the years.
But gradually, for a number of reasons, got less and less interested in continuing and started phasing it out, doing less and less of it.
One reason for being less interested was that, as far as the early part of it, reality was catching up with me.
Not only were public or political events not working out on my timetable.
For example, World War III did not come off on schedule.
But also, it turned out I had failed to foresee a number of scientific and technological developments.
So, I was going into other things.
But you're probably thinking, though, about this much larger and more enduring project of mine,
which has sometimes been called the League and Empire series or something like that.
Now, that has a history much more like that of Topsy.
Originally, I'd written a few stories about Nicholas Van Rijn.
And I'd written a few stories about Dominic Flandry, who lived in completely different milieus, of course.
And then one day, on an impulse, I thought, well, gosh, they could be on the same timeline, one living about 500 years after the other.
And threw in mention of that in one of the Flandry stories.
And then started fitting in other stories, wherever it was convenient.
You see, the thing with the future history is that, although each story should, of course, be readable independently of any others,
and comprehensible and so on, nevertheless, if you have a reader who remembers a number of them,
the cross-connections will add an extra dimension, and thereby, I hope, add to his enjoyment.
So, I started doing it that way.
And after a while, I realized I had a rather large beast by the tail.
If I was going to stay consistent at all, then I had to keep careful notes, and I had to develop a systematic scheme and so on.
And thus, over the years, one thing led to another, until it all became rather elaborate.
By now, it includes, oh, I think something like 40 separate items, of which probably at least a third or so are full-dress novels.
But I've probably carried it about as far as it can go.
I doubt I'll do much more, if anything, in that line.
Instead, I'd rather go on to something else.
